{
  "texts": [
    "Deep-learning-based segmentation algorithms like Cellpose 2.0 [111], Mesmer [112], and Segment Anything [113] have shown superior performance to more traditional algorithms like watershed [114] but are highly sensitive to cell diameter and shape.",
    "This is problematic, as tissues like the heart are composed of cells with vastly different morphology.",
    "Human cardiomyocytes are cylindrically shaped with an approximate length and diameter of around 100 μm and 20 μm, respectively [115], which is much larger than interstitial or immune cells for example.",
    "Furthermore, they can be multinucleated [116] and vary in shape based on the sectioning of the tissue and disease progression [117].",
    "This poses significant difficulties for deep-learning algorithms, which were not trained on a large corpus of heart data, necessitating fine-tuning."
  ]
}